\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 9th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 December 1943}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (covering period from 30th November to 7th December, 1943)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 I. GENERAL COMMENTS
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 1. GENERAL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Public satisfaction with war events has increased this week, thanks to the new offensive in Italy, the raids on Germany, Russian advances and the meeting at Teheran "between the three great men".
\par 
\par Nevertheless spirits have risen only a little: the flu epidemic is the chief topic for most people, and general tiredness, ill-health and the black-out are the cause of some depression.
\par 
\par The release of the Mosleys continues to be widely discussed, but with less vehemence - though much resentment is still simmering.
\par 
\par The ballot scheme for securing labour for the mines has had a mixed, but on the whole favourable reception.
\par 
\par Domestic Front: Much talk of Christmas, chiefly about the prospects of getting a turkey, and the price and quality of toys. Post-war prospects, housing and footwear continue to be anxiously discussed. 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17 and 18 passim)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 2. THE ALLIED CONFERENCES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par The news of the two conferences has given much satisfaction, but so far there has been only limited comment. This is thought to be because people are waiting for more precise information before expressing opinions, because the news did not come as a co
mplete surprise, and because there is some impatience with so many conferences which talk of the final assault.
\par 
\par The Cairo Conference: The first reactions were surprise and pleasure at the presence of General Chiang Kai-Shek, end disappointment at the
 absence of Marshal Stalin. This disappointment largely disappeared with the news of the Teheran conference, though there was still some regret and failure to understand why the Russian and Chinese leaders can never meet. Most people are glad to have Chin
a once more "in the picture" - as with many, workers especially, she comes second in popularity only to Russia - end there is great satisfaction et the comprehensive plans for fighting the Japanese.
\par 
\par The declaration of punishment to be meted out to Japan went further them some had expected, but has met with very wide approval Nine Regions). There is, however, minority criticism from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13531764 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
a) those who are tired of "fist-shaking" and want to see words translated into action, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (b) those who feel that the problem of Japan's expanding population will still have to be solved,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (c) those who fear threats will only stiffen her resistance and may provoke her to atrocities.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par The Teheran Conference: Only preliminary reports have been received so far, but people appear 
to be far more interested in this than in the Cairo Conference. There is great satisfaction - and some enthusiasm - that at last the three great leaders have come together; though Marshal Stalin has been criticised for "only going 60 miles out of his own 
c
ountry", while the other two had to go so far. People hope that all misunderstandings between the western democracies and Russia have now been smoothed away, that the future of Poland has been satisfactorily settled, and all arrangements made for the fina
l assault on Germany. Meanwhile they are pleased at the apparent friendliness of the proceedings and eagerly await further information.
\par 
\par There is so far little comment on the joint declaration, but, according to the Scottish report, "the fact that Stali
n's signature appears on it gives evidence to many - especially workers - that the document will be honoured. Greater faith is placed in Stalin's word than in any ether statesman's."
\par 
\par The release of news: Criticism of "the mishandling of publicity" is 
mentioned in reports from eight Regions, two of which, however, suggest that it comes largely from press circles or the "more informed". Nevertheless many people seem annoyed that other countries, and especially the U.S.A., should have heard the news befo
re we did; and the fact that the Cairo conference to some extent "fell flat" is thought to be because news came through first from enemy and neutral sources.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13. 18 passim)
\par 
\par 3. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 THE HOSLEYS' RELEASE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Excitement has su
bsided considerably, and many are now speaking of "a storm in a tea-cup", and asking: "Why all the fuss?" But there are still many particularly working people who feel strong that the Hosleys should not have been released. There is no change in the argume
nts they use:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13531764 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
(i) One law for the rich and another for the poor. Mosley would not have got out had he not been a rich men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (ii) Phlebitis is no excuse. Holloway is ideal for its treatment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (iii) It is a compromise with fascism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par Among the growing number who approve the Home Secretary's action are some who nevertheless think that the timing was inappropriate.
\par 
\par Mr. Morrison is now fairly widely praised for acting courageously according to his convictions in the face of popular clamour, and 
for his skilful speech in the Debate. There is more comment that opposition was deliberately whipped up to spite the Home Secretary
\par 
\par In the East End, there are fears of recrudescence of facism and rumours that the British Union of Fascists has taken an old hall in Paddington for meetings.
\par 
\par 18B is again criticised, though the, majority appear to have no understanding of it.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13. 17 twelve provincial P.Cs. 18 passim)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 4. ITALY }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par The news that we are again moving forward is generally described as heartening. It is thought we still have a stiff job on hand, end the most optimists hope for is Rome by Christmas. There is much sympathy for the troops, and it is feared casualties ma
y be heavy. More details of conditions under which fighting is going on arc asked for.
\par 
\par The political situation is little mentioned. There is disgust at stories of Italians being allowed to fleece our men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 passim)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 5. ALLIED AIR OFFENSIVE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par There is again great interest in the raids en German territory, especially Berlin. They are looked on as a "gruesome necessity" to make future land operations less costly. There is much speculation .s to their effec
t on German morale. Though there is some sympathy for civilians, people generally are thought to display "neither tenderness nor exultation" over the victims; any tendency to "gloat" over their sufferings is disliked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 Concern is}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953  reported over the number of bombers lost, especially in the raid of December 2nd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.5.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17 ten provincial P.Cs. 18 passim)
\par 
\par 6. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 REPRISALS END SECRET WEAPONS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par In London it appears that a majority are now giving some thought to the possibility
 of a retaliatory secret weapon. Indeed, many are anxious about it, though there are still a large number who laugh at the idea. "Frightening tales" are repented "on good authority". It is rumoured that rockets have already fallen on London - in. Park Lan
e
, the Borough High Street, and somewhere in the West End, There appears to be some confusion between rockets of British and German origin; thus, pockets are said to have been fired at Civil Defence practices. It is also rumoured that the Government is exp
ecting large-scale gas attacks, and huge stocks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
of bleach powder are-said to have been delivered at decontamination centres. Evening theatre end cinema attendances are thought to have declined.
\par 
\par In the rest of the country, there is a good deal of discu
ssion about reprisals, though much less anxiety and more skepticism. Secret weapons are less discussed, though a large-scale gas attack on London is thought conceivable. Anything much anywhere else is not expected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.5.SE.6.7.8.10.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 twelve P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13531764 7. RAIDS ON THIS COUNTRY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par The recent raid on Plymouth is still producing comment on the lack of defences.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par In Deal, it is said that people have noticed with dismay the removal of A.A. defences from the town) and in. view of threatened reprisals would feel much happier if they could be returned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (5SE.7)
\par 
\par 8.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 GENERAL SMUTS' ADDRESS (NOVEMBER 25)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par This has provoked much thought and discussion. On the whole it has been very highly praised, especially for its candour and realism though a number of people have been disturbed and feel this is not the moment to throw explosives about.
\par 
\par Disapproving comment is more detailed, than approving, and has particularly centred round his references to:
\par 
\par France (Eight Regions): Though the realism of his references to post-war France is praised, they have caused some surprise and regret, and arc thought t
o be rather ill-timed and a "rich plum" for German propaganda. It is thought that the ardour of the French whether Fighting or otherwise - will be damped.
\par 
\par Russia, "the Colossus" (Five Regions): This, too, was considered ill-timed by some, and likely to pave the way for still more distrust of Russia.
\par 
\par "Britain will be poor" (Four Regions) : Some anxiety and failure to understand the reason for this. A few ask what is to cone of the "grandiose" post-war schemes, if we are to be so poor.
\par 
\par Splittin
g up the Empire into zones (Two Regions): Some suspect an attempt to secure native territories of South Africa for the Union, and consider that coloured peoples are likely to be less well treated under the Dutch or South African flag than under the Britis
h.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.5.5SE.7.8.13)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 9. RUSSIA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Administration of the Russian successes and her continued progress continues, though the slight withdrawals caused some anxiety. The feeling is again expressed that the Russians are winning the war for us and it is time we relieved them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17 six P.Cs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 passim)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 10. THE LEBANON}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Comment continues on familiar lines and has decreased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.6.7.10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17 two provincial P.Cs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 nineteen P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 11. LEROS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Comment continues on familiar lines and has decreased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 7 three provincial P.Cs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 passim)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 12. TURKEY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par (No reports since the news of the second Cairo Conference)
\par Speculation as to Turkey's possible entry into the war has recurred - in London it was recently rumoured that she had come in, with resulting intense satisfaction.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 There is still some feeling, however, that our loss of the Dodecanese islands has prejudiced the possibility of Turkey becoming our ally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.4.5.6.10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 five P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par 13. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 WAR AT SEA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks general satisfaction with our successes against the U-boats has been reported. The figures of U-boat losses have acted "as a tonic".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.6.7.8.9.10.13.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 14. BROADCASTING AND PRESENTATION OF NEWS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Apart from references to the release of news of the Allied Conferences (q.v.) there is little comment on news presentation; but there is still some complaint of inaccuracy and repetition, Some people feel that the B.B
.C. bulletins have been "soft-pedalling" on Russian withdrawals.
\par 
\par Programmes: The improved standard of drama productions is appreciated and more plays are asked for. More light music is wanted and people are thought to tune in to foreign stations to get it. There is comment on the poor quality of variety programmes.

\par 
\par Sir Norman Angell's postscript November 28 (Eight Regions) was appreciated. It was thought to be "brilliant, logical, and needing to be said".
\par 
\par General: Praise for Major Hastings' war commentary, December 2. (Four Regions); "The Air is our Concern" (Three Regions); Brains' Trust, St. Andrews's night (Two Regions); Theodor Brach's postscript December 5 (Two Regions).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 II. SPECIAL COMMENTS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par FULL MONTHLY REVIEW
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 15. POST-WAR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks comment on post-war matters has continued widespread. Uneasiness seems to be deepening; in some cases anxiety has become pessimism. The appointment of a Minister for Reconstruction, the Prime-Minister's prom
ise of "food, work and homes for all", and the emphasis on post-war matters in the King's speech, although serving temporarily to raise hopes, have had no appreciable lasting effect.
\par 
\par Cynicism about the possibilities of a "better and brighter" world af
ter the war is increasing, The "shelving" of the Beveridge and other Reports and White Papers, the "lack of definite proposals" and the "nebulousness" of promises are criticised, and are taken as evidence that the Government is really little interested in
 post-war matters..."All this talk is merely window-dressing". "Definite action" is called for and is considered by many to be the only likelihood of reassuring people.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6970953 Increasingly pessimistic comparison is being math, with "what happened last time".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
Housing: Post-war housing continues to arouse widespread concern, particularly among those married since the war and so far dependent on relatives, or living in furnished rooms. A "wild scramble" when the war ends is feared to be likely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 The del
ay in announcing plans for housing is strongly criticised, Apart from impatience that building is being held up, it is feared that lack of guiding policy will result in "jerry-building coming into its own again", in speculation in land, and "the same sham
eful exploitation which took place after the last war". The buying up of land and premises "more or less surreptitiously going on at present" is already causing some concern.
\par 
\par There is little detailed comment on the kind of home wanted, though women are becoming increasingly interested and arc demand in more say in the planning of houses. The preference for small houses rather than flats is mentioned.
\par 
\par Employment: Fears of post-war unemployment are widespread, par}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 ticularly, it is said}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953  in the Forces
. "Flooding" of the labour market after the war is dreaded and there is much discussion of the prospects of those in the Forces and armament industries; and of women.
\par 
\par In the mining, cotton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 heavy industries generally there is acute anxiety about anothe
r "slump". ''Prospects of a return to normal conditions mean to the people in the coalfield, and in heavy industry generally, a return to unemployment and the dole." In the Northern Region, the introduction of light industries into the district is demande
d, to ease the employment problem after the war.
\par 
\par Education: Discussion of educational reform has continued and has become rather more general; though still chiefly limited to those professionally interested. The raising}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6970953 the school-leaving age}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 which i
t is hoped will help to lesson unemployment - the need for educational apprenticeship, and the "religious side" all arouse interest.
\par 
\par Opposition to the White Paper from religious bodies is criticised, and it is hoped \'93The Government will be ruthless in
 its determination to make no concession". Some-minority fears are entertained, however, that "under the cloak of improving education, plans are afoot to educate all in a common mould".
\par 
\par Post-war Controls: Post-war controls continue to arouse discussion though on a reduced scale. The public are prepared to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
admit that some controls will be needed after the war, and in some cases urge them as a means of preventing speculation and "racketeering". Nevertheless they are tired of "continual interference and f
orm-filling", and "there will be trouble if this is not kept within reasonable bounds".
\par 
\par It is felt that some definite, official statements should be made about post-war control, because at present it is not clear if the utterances of Ministers are expressions of the Government's views.
\par 
\par Agriculture: Anxiety about post-war farming continues. Farmers and labourers are said to be equally concerned about the Government's future attitude. Better wages and housing for agricultural labourers are urged as means of keeping men on the land.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 Local authorities: The future of Local authorities is the subject of some discussion (Two Regions). There is said to be some uneasiness about Whitehall's "increasing control" over local affairs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11. 17.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 fifteen P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15619737 16. HOUSING AND BILLETING }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks the shortage of all kinds of housing accommodation has continued to be the cause of considerable anxiety. In many cases it has become "one of the most immediate and pressing problems on the Home Front".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 The Government's delay in "getting a move on" is criticised and it is feared that a chaotic position would result if the war were to end soon.
\par 
\par Particular reference is made to the difficulties experienced by:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13650166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (a) War brides (Five Regions). Many of them who have remained at home with their parents already have children, and are becoming increasingly anxious to set up homes of their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (b) Families of servicemen (Two Regions). There are again complaints that landlords will not let to them for fear of "bad debts".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (c) Couples with children, and 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (d) Old people (One Region each).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par The high rents of houses, flats and rooms- furnished and unfurnished- continue to excite bitter comment (Seven Regions). It is again urged that rents for furnished rooms should be controlled.
\par 
\par The "ramp" in the buying and selling of houses at exorbitant prices is also criticised (Four Regions). A "ceiling" on the price of houses, based on pre-war values, is urged.
\par 
\par Repairs: Difficulties in getting repairs done are complained of (Four Regions). Even where repairs have been carried out they are said not to stand up at all well to the rain. In London there are also complaints of the delay
 in repairing bomb-damaged houses "until an investigation has been made by the Council".
\par 
\par Local Authorities' requisitioning powers: Disappointment continues to be expressed (Two Regions). "Either there is nothing to requisition, or all talk and no do" results.
\par 
\par Agricultural housing: The delay in the building of the agricultural cottages continues to arouse comment (Four Regions).
\par 
\par Billeting: In the Eastern and Southern Regions billeting difficulties are said to remain a source of dissatisfaction. 
In the Southern Region particularly, it is felt that the housewife is sufficiently harassed without having people billeted on her and that after four years of war, hostels should by now have boon provided.
\par 
\par In the South Western Region and in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 there have been some complaints at the-thought of having to billet American troops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17. 18 one P.D.R.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 17. MINERS AND MINING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 The ballot system: Comment has been considerable and reactions have been as follows:
\par 
\par Approval: The majority among both miners and the general public think it is a good idea because they feel it will be fair to all (Ten Regions).
\par 
\par Disapproval: An appreciable minority disapprove or qualify their acceptance, because they believe:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13650166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
(a) There will be "loopholes" by which the rich will gain exemption (Four Regions), e.g. by reason of their "education".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (b) It would be better to withdraw trained miners from the Forces. Miners, in particular, feel that "green" labour will be of little use for many months (Four Regions).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par There is some sympathy for those who are chosen and parents are said to be "aghast". It is reported that young men in the Northern Region say they would rather go to gaol than down a mine; they are said to be volunteering for air crews end the Navy.

\par 
\par Nothing but disapproval is reported from the Midland Region, where it is thought that it will only result in more square pegs in round holes. Simpler folk wonder how they will get all the names into one hat.
\par 
\par During the past four weeks concern about the coal mining situation has continued.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 The following are thought chiefly to account for trouble and difficulties:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13650166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (a) Unpopularity of Government man-power measures (Five Regions), in particular:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li851\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0\pararsid13650166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (i) The introduction of "green labo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13650166 ur", which miners in particular }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 fool will increase accidents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (ii) The direction of young boys to the mines and their prosecution for absenteeism. (Since the announcement of the ballot system there has}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13650166  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 been less criticism on these lines).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid13650166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par (b) Miners' remembrance of the way they were treated after the lost war and their concern about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 future of the industry (Four Regions).
\par 
\par (c) Conditions of work in general, and particularly the lack of up-to-date machinery in some mince (Three Regions).
\par 
\par (d) Disparity of wages between mining and other industries (Two Regions).
\par 
\par (e) "Subversive influences" in the coal-fields (One Region).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par Remedies: Many feel that nationalisation is the only solution (Five Regions). Extra food rations and a shorter working week are other suggestions (Two Regions each).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11. 17.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 twelve P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 18. DOMESTIC FUEL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Supplies of cool: People in. the Northern, North Eastern, North Midland and London Regions wonder how they will manage on the coal allowance this winter. Supply difficulties ore reported from Norfolk. 
\par 
\par Economy campaign: There is little interest in the 
campaign. Opinion is divided as to the effort being made to economise. There is some feeling that people resent exhortations and feel rather that firmer action against strikers and greater economy in large organizations is needed (Three Regions).
\par 
\par Waste of full is alleged in London stores, offices - especially American promises, and Fun Fairs (Three Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.7.9.10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6970953 18 seven P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 19. INDUSTRY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Press accounts of the action taken by}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 Ministry of Labour
\par against Desoutters, for ignoring a direction, has heartened work-people, who think that "at last" the Essential Work Order is being used impartially.
\par 
\par During the past four weeks comment has been mainly en the following topics:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7681550 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (a) Tiredness among workers, especiall
y the young (Eight Regions) - thought by the majority to be duo to excessively long hours.
\par 
\par (b) Enforced idleness and overstaffing (Seven Regions). There are a number of complaints of idle and wasted time in war factories, particularly in the Northern 
Region. Complaints are also made of needless work (e.g. building a wall and pulling it down again), due, according to workers, to the employers' desire to swell costs and thus obtain the added percentage of profit.
\par 
\par (c) Slackness of workers and absenteeism (Seven Regions). This causes some concern and is thought, in part, to be due to illness and the lack of the stimulant of intense military activity; though also to indifference, particularly among youths.
\par 
\par (d) Disparities in wages (Six Regions): Ag
ain this month particular mention is made of the disparity between skilled and unskilled workers' wages. It is said that skilled workers in the North Midland Region try for this reason to get work en unskilled operations.
\par 
\par (e) High wades (Six Regions): Complaints are mostly of the high wages paid to factory workers compared with the Forces and workers still on peace-time salaries.
\par 
\par (e) Dismissal of workers and unemployment (Five Regions):
\par There is a considerable amount of talk of the dismissal of war workers and of unemployment, particularly in the Northern and Midland Regions and Wales. Rumours are also reported of the closing down of war factories.
\par 
\par (g) Changes in production (Five Regions): Reports speak of pre
paration for post-war production already being made and of fears among workers of a "return to soulless industrial competition". Even where the change-over is to work in preparation for relief in occupied countries, workers are said to lose their feeling 
of urgency and to feel they are no longer needed to win the war.
\par 
\par (h) Transfer of women (Five Regions): This causes complaints and is considered a sign of bad management of labour.
\par 
\par (i) Over-production (Four Regions): Some believe that output has exceeded requirements in many directions.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.5.4.5.5SE.6.7.8. 9.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 17)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 20. STRIKES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par A slight decrease in comment this week: (Nine Regions) thought the great majority continue to condemn strikes in wartime; a small number still feel that workers have no other means of improving conditions.
\par 
\par During the past four weeks various suggestions as to the cause of strikes have been made:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7681550 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (a) Lack of firm action on the part of the Government (Eight Regions)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (b) Failings on the part of employers (Four Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (c) Tiredness and war weariness (Three Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (d) Inability of Trades Unions to control their members (Three Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (e) The inefficient functioning of negotiating machinery (Three Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (f) Paid agitators and Fifth Columnists (Three Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (g) Communists and "Trotskyites" (Two Regions).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
