\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 31. SHOPPING DIFFICULTIES AND FOOD QUEUES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks complaints have been fewer (Eight Regions), hut on familiar lines,
 and very strong in the London Region where shopping is described as "a nightmare for the working woman" (See Constant Topics, No.6). The lunch-time and earlier winter closing of shops still seems to be the greatest cause of difficulties, and workers are 
still the section of the public to suffer most. People grumble that shopping is very tiring and wastes so much time.
\par 
\par There are again complaints of:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li567\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin567\itap0\pararsid7681550 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (a) The quota system whereby goods in short supply are put on sale at 10 a.m. or later and are sold out before lunch time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
(b) The comparatively poor stock of food in rural shops, which involves rural housewives in travelling to the nearest town, where they often find that goods on points or in short supply have already been sold.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (c) The ordering of goods by telephone, to the detriment of personal shoppers.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6970953 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (2.4.5.5SE.8.9.10.11)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 32. OLD AGE PENSIONS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par The improved standard of supplementary pensions, which will come into force on January 17 if approved by Parliament, has boon welcomed (Three Regions), though many people feel that en increase in the basic pension is needed.
\par 
\par During the past four weeks there have been repeated references to the inadequacy of old age pensions, in view of the increased cost of living, and to the wish for their increase}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (Seven Regions 'Sec Constant Topics, No.7). Some feel that, in addition to an increase, there should be en extra food allowance - especially mill - and "less probing into the most intimate conditions of a pensioner".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.8.9.10)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 33. INCOME TAX}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks approval for the "pay-as-you-earn" scheme has continued (Five Regions). There are still many people who would like a clear and simple explanation of it, end a broadcast on the subject (December 3) was praised.
\par 
\par Managements continue to complain of the extra amount of work for their staff that will be involved
, and some fear they will have to engage extra accountants. Those not concerned with operating the scheme, however, hope it will not be shelved because of the extra labour needed.
\par 
\par Post-war credits: Some people fear that post-war credits will merely be credited to them against income tax, and not paid in cash.
\par 
\par Irish workers: Bitter comment is reported about Irish workers who return to Eire after six months, without paying tax (North Midland Region).
\par 
\par Slacking to avoid paying tax is still reported. The case is mentioned of a nurse who said she was obliged to take far longer holidays than she used to, as otherwise she would be liable for tax.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.9)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 34. SERVICEMEN'S PENSIONS AND DEPENDANTS' ALLOWANCES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four
 weeks, there have again been complaints of the inadequacy of Service pensions - whether for dependants or for the men themselves (Four Regions), and of dependants' allowances (Three Regions, See Constant Topics, No.13).. There is, however, some feeling t
hat the general treatment of cases has improved and there is praise for the work of the Pensions Appeals Tribunals; it is thought that more publicity about them might do good. There is, too, appreciation of the grant to widows for rent.
\par 
\par Specific complaints mentioned (One Region each) are:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7681550 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
(a) Employers arc discouraged from making up the pay of their employees who join up, because the amount allowed by the firm will be deducted' from the War Service Grant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (b) The hardship incurred, due to the time lag between the reduction of a woman's War Service Grant and the increased allotment made to her husband.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (c) The reduction in a dependant's allowance if she takes paid employment. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 (d) The inclusion of a widow's Service pension for income tax.
