\par 35. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 HOME GUARD, FIRE-WATCHING AND CIVIL DEFENCE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par Fire watching duties: During the past two weeks criticism has continued on lines previously reported, though the recent announce
ment of some alleviation of duty in areas where this can safely be made has given satisfaction. There is disappointment in some districts where no release is possible. One report states "the present increase in illness has brought fresh gr
umbles, and in industrial areas there is strong evidence of the deplorable effect of fire-watching on miners, heavy workers and housewives".
\par 
\par Home Guard: Complaints have continued of the amount of duty required, particularly from workers already employ
ed for long hours and those who have already trained for many Months. But keen members of the Home Guard again criticise it Walter Citrine's speech as implying a doubt of the value of their services and providing wavering members with an exclusive for shi
r
king. They advocate a greater insistence on attendances. It is thought that the "browned-off" feeling persists probably because it no longer seems evident that the Home Guard has a function to perform, One report suggests that what is wanted is not a cutt
ing down of the Home Guard but more time off, and that one 3unday n month would have a tremendous effect.
\par 
\par Civil Defence: It is suggested in one report, that full-time C.D. personnel could, be detailed for work in shops and offices near their Headquarters.
\par (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 1.2.3.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 18 six P.D.Rs.) 
