\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550 36. BLACK-OUT }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks there has again been a comment on the depressing effect of the black-out, which some think might now be modified, especially in inland areas. Some people
 ask why side roads cannot have star-lighting like main roads. In London it is thought that grumbles have died down sharply since the raid on Putney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 On the other hand laxity of black-out is criticised in some quarters and it is thought that torches 
used by people living buildings must show up more than scattered lights. Pedestrians, motorists and cyclists, all complain of the dangerous flashing of torches, and of the blinding effect of headlights with badly adjusted masks. Drivers who adhere to regu
lations are often at a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7681550  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 disadvantage.
