\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 HOME INTELLIGENCE WEEKLY REPORT
\par 
\par The aim of this Report is to present an impartial assessment of public feeling about the war and the war effort. It is not a record of fact, except in so far as public opinion is itself a fact.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10909220  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970953 The public is sometimes ill-informed, prejudiced, or inconsistent. The recording of such feelings without comment implies no endorsement of them.
\par 
\par The public is more prone to criticise than to praise. Good work or efficiency is usually taken for granted in accurate record of expressed feeling will, therefore,
 tend to be critical rather than laudatory. Though this Report must inevitably represent mainly articulate opinion, it has been found in practice that the views of the less articulate do not substantially differ, though their range is smaller.
\par 
\par The met
hod of compiling the Report is such that the amount of space devoted to each subject, and the order in which subjects are placed, are roughly indicative of the amount of public interest each is arousing. The omission of a subject from the Report means tha
t it is not a matter of widespread comment.
\par 
\par In assessing the state of public feeling there are no absolutes. Findings can only be comparative. Each Issue of this Report must therefore be road as part of a continuous series. Unless the series is seen a
s a whole, the significance of fluctuations in feeling cannot be appreciated.
\par 
\par The figures in brackets at the end of each section refer to sources of information, a list of which is given on the next page. The weekly reports from Regional Information O
fficers (R.I.Os.) are compiled by their Regional Intelligence Officers from a large number of sources. Details of the methods of compilation and cross-checking are contained in paper on "Hew the Home Intelligence Weekly Report is made." This will be suppl
ied on request to the Homo Intelligence Division of the Ministry of Information.
